```python
return {"name": name, "age":age}
```
In this case, **/hello** is the route, followed by two parameters put in curly brackets. If the URL given in the browser’s address bar is <u>
http://localhost:8000/hello/Ravi/20
</u>, The data of Ravi and 20 will be assigned to variables name and age respectively. The browser displays the following JSON response:
```json
{"name":"Ravi","age":"20"}
```
## Path Parameters with Types
You can use Python’s type hints for the parameters of the function to be decorated. In this case, define name as str and age as int.
```python
@app.get("/hello/{name}/{age}")
async def hello(name:str,age:int):
    return {"name": name, "age":age}
```
This will result in the browser displaying an HTTP error message in the JSON response if the types don’t match. Try entering <u>
http://localhost:8000/hello/20/Ravi
</u> as the URL. The browser’s response will be as follows:
```json
{
  "detail": [
    {
      "loc": [
        "path",
        "age"
      ],
      "msg": "value is not a valid integer",
      "type": "type_error.integer"
    }
  ]
}
```

